##Why don't European countries still advise people to wear masks?

Weixin Signal Wowjiemian

Function introduction, the interface news is China has the influence original financial and economic new media, only serves the independent thinking crowd

Visual China

REPORTER: Wang Qing

“

Europe is now entering a period of surge in cases and is facing many challenges similar to those in the early days of the Chinese outbreak.

”

“

Europe is now entering a period of surge in cases and is facing many challenges similar to those in the early days of the Chinese outbreak.

”

As new crown disease spreads across Europe, countries are running out of masks. On February 29th the French government announced that face masks would be listed as a prescription drug. Pharmacies are not allowed to sell masks to customers who do not have a doctor's prescription, to limit looting and to leave masks for those who need protection most.

According to the interface news, in Milan, Paris, London, Brussels, Amsterdam and other major cities, pharmacies are out of masks, disinfection supplies shortage phenomenon. In contrast, masks are still rarely seen on the streets of major European cities except in northern Italy.

Where are all these masks? Medical supplies have always been sufficient in Europe, why are suddenly caught in a "mask shortage" ? How are European governments and companies responding to this challenge?

###It's already in short supply

As of press time, 18 EU member states have reported new cases of coronary disease, including Italy, a disaster area, a cumulative 2,036 cases, France and Germany confirmed cases are more than 100. The European Union has raised the risk level of the outbreak from "moderate" to "high" . The outbreak in Europe began on February 21 with a community outbreak in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , northern Italy, but supplies of masks were showing signs of shortages long before that.

Although the Netherlands did not confirm its first case until Feb. 27, masks were already in short supply at the end of January, mostly purchased by Asian groups, an employee at a pharmacy in Amsterdam told interface news. The pharmacy was going to increase its purchases, but it was already hard to find supplies.

The German Association of Pharmaceutical Wholesalers said last week that pharmacies are having difficulty getting new supplies and, even if orders are successful, often face delays and shipping difficulties.

In Italy, the epicenter of the outbreak, the price of face masks has skyrocketed hundreds of times. Reuters quoted a Milan prosecutor as saying that the online price of an ordinary mask in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. Had Risen to 10 euros from the usual 1 Euro cents, forcing the police to investigate.

Many Chinese living in Italy, France and Britain told interface news that face masks were already hard to find in brick-and-mortar pharmacies, and online stores often showed that they were out of stock, if you want to buy a mask, you have to go through the Chinese community "self-seeking channels. ".

Not only consumers but also health care workers have expressed concern about the shortage of face masks.

Doctors at the University Hospital in Rostock, Germany, told Deutsche Welle that the biggest problem they face is that they can not buy protective masks, university Hospital suppliers say they can supply six months'supply, but it is not clear how they approach it. In extreme cases, there is a high likelihood that the mask will need to be reused.

Italian nurses union told Italian media that masks, protective clothing, gloves and other protective clothing is seriously missing, many areas have run out. In the Tuscany region, there have even been cases of masks being stolen from hospitals.

###Why is it so short?

The New York Times pointed out that China is both the center of the new Crown Epidemic and the center of mask production in the world. China produces about 50 percent of the world's masks each year, and the outbreak in Wuhan, combined with the Lunar New Year holiday, has shut down many factories. China then issued control measures on the export of epidemic-prevention materials. Before the outbreak, they exported 600,000 to 700,000 surgical masks a month, but that number is now zero, said the president of a ningbo-based Foreign Trade Company. The global market, including Europe, has long been unable to get regular supplies of masks from China.

In the early stage of the epidemic, the existing stocks of masks in Europe were used in large quantities to aid China. In early February, at the request of the Chinese side, the EU coordinated member states to deliver 12 tons of urgently needed materials for epidemic prevention and control to China. Since the city closure of Wuhan, a large number of Chinese living in Europe through retail or wholesale, in Europe to buy and transport home, especially the overseas Chinese Association and the Wuhan Area of the University Alumni Association as the main force.

According to Interface News, there are also individual Chinese traders in Europe to take advantage of information about the time gap, stockpiling masks and selling them to local people at high prices. According to information circulating on some chinese-european wechat groups, "50pz box masks, which normally cost 2.5(euros) , have been sold for 20,50,100 and even Lion's Share for 200 euros. ". Therefore, some overseas Chinese workers come out and appeal to the European Chinese businessmen to stop hoarding masks and put some to local medical staff.

###Capacity Challenges

The shortage of face masks in many countries poses a serious challenge to Europe's manufacturing capacity.

According to Vittorio de Blasiis, head of Il Sole 24 Ore, the country's mask-making company, DPI Roma, in mid-february, "the last decade's stock of masks was consumed in 10 days. ". He said he was receiving millions of orders every day because of the surge in demand. Not only are there procurement requests from China, but also from large international companies wishing to procure for their employees.

However, most of the European mask manufacturers are based in China and Europe itself has very limited capacity. As China bans exports of medical masks, some manufacturers are planning to move production back home or to other countries that have not been affected by the outbreak.

According to the Czech News Portal Irozhlas, demand for masks made by Czech Medical Supply Company Repilon, which supplies the European and American markets, has increased more than tenfold since the outbreak. The company's usual production process is: by the Czech Republic mask production of raw materials, processed in China.

Roman Zima, the company's President, said it was considering new production lines in the Czech Republic and Israel, which could start production in May and produce 70,000 face masks and 6,000 medical masks a day. But he said it was still unlikely to meet actual demand. Europe currently has three major mask manufacturers, which is not enough from a strategic point of view.

###Government emergency deployment

European governments have also introduced emergency deployment measures. The priority is to make sure that there are enough face masks for all health care workers.

Among EU member states, France was the first to respond to the shortage of masks. The French government announced last week that it had placed an urgent order for 200m masks, but it was not certain when they would arrive. The government has distributed a stockpile of 15 million masks to the medical front, mainly to support family doctors and hospital workers. On February 29th France decided to include face masks in its prescriptions to prevent panic buying.

Italy's central and local governments also launched a round of mask purchases last week. According to Corriere della Sera, the government of Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. has urgently procured 300,000 FFP3 masks and 200,000 medical masks. Angelo Borrelli, a member of Italy's "new Crown Crisis Committee" , said the central government had set up a special procurement channel for masks in cooperation with Confindustria, the Italian Federation of Industrialists, the masks will be distributed upon their arrival in accordance with the epidemic situation in each region.

The Italian government has yet to impose restrictions on the purchase of face masks, but has stepped up efforts to crack down on reselling such as malicious price hikes. In Turin, police recently uncovered a sale of illegal face masks, a box of which sold for up to 5,000 euros.

The UK government also said it would release some of its stock of masks to ease pressure on demand. The German government has also issued a notice to pharmacies, priority to protect the needs of health care workers mask.

The European Commission said at a press conference on March 2 that the European Union had coordinated the purchase of supplies, including face masks, by 18 affected member states. They expect to receive the materials within a week, but have not yet disclosed the size of the procurement.

The European Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (ECDC) said in an earlier interview with interface news that EU countries may activate pandemic preparedness plans to ensure the health system has sufficient resources and manpower to isolate and treat the growing number of new patients.

###"people don't need masks. "

It's worth noting that the Italian, French, German, British and other governments have issued official vaccination manuals advising the general public whether or not to wear face masks: No. As of press time, at least 30 European countries (excluding Russia) have reported confirmed cases, including 2,036 in Italy, 191 in France, 157 in Germany and 40 in the United Kingdom.

On the whole, these European country's epidemic prevention manual all followed WHO's recommendation, it emphasizes washing hands frequently, covering your arms when coughing or sneezing, using disposable tissues, avoiding handshakes and unnecessary physical contact.

The NHS says masks are important in places such as hospitals, but there is little evidence that covering the nose and mouth with a mask reduces the risk of contracting the new coronavirus in healthy people. The main function of masks is to prevent patients from spreading the disease to others, so those who have symptoms need to wear masks.

The Italian Health Ministry, citing the World Health Organization organisation, said masks should be worn only by people who may have come in contact with the patient, those who have had symptoms such as coughing or sneezing, and those who are caring for suspected or confirmed patients, and the medical staff at the hospital. In addition, people should wear masks in Romagné, Florida, Lombardy and Veneto, the red areas of northern Italy.

Germany's Health Ministry said that the general population wearing masks "does not make sense" , should focus on the epidemic prevention of personal hygiene. Wearing a mask in the right way (a bearded man, for example, needs to shave first) and changing it frequently is the only way to reduce the risk of infection. Wearing a mask can also create a false sense of security and lead to the neglect of other hygiene measures, such as frequent hand washing. The Ministry of Health recommends that people with flu-related symptoms talk to their family doctor before deciding whether, how and which type of mask to wear.

The French Health Ministry recommends that you wear a mask if you have been to affected areas in the past two weeks, such as China, Singapore, South Korea, Iran and northern Italy. However, it is emphasized that respirators with suction valves, such as FFP2, should be left to medical personnel.

However, according to Interface News, the Chinese community in Europe have some doubts about these recommendations.

China is experiencing a "hard core" epidemic prevention, in which face masks are the basic materials for people's epidemic prevention. In places where the epidemic is serious, there have even been compulsory measures not to wear face masks on the streets. By contrast, some Chinese worry that the EU's 500m people may be a strategic gesture by European governments to prevent panic buying when masks are in short supply, not because they really don't work.
